{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-f95dae45-3dad-91c1-a190-28d8d429d73f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"auto","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Great! All three drugs are available in the formulary:\n\n1. **Omeprazole** (奥美拉唑): PPI, ATC A02BC01, NRDL A (fully reimbursed, no restrictions)\n2. **Hydrotalcite** (铝碳酸镁): Antacid, ATC A02AD02, NRDL A (fully reimbursed, no restrictions)\n3. **Domperidone** (多潘立酮): Prokinetic, ATC A03FA03, NRDL B (partially self-paid, no restrictions)\n\nNow let me construct the prescription. Here's my clinical reasoning:\n\n**Patient**: 23-year-old male, 72kg, acute simple gastritis (K29.1) caused by dietary stimulus (spicy hotpot + cold beer)\n\n**Clinical assessment**:\n- No bacterial infection (WBC normal, neutrophils normal)\n- No GI bleeding signs\n- Normal renal and hepatic function\n- No allergies\n- No comorbidities\n- No current medications (no interaction concerns)\n\n**Treatment plan**:\n1. **Omeprazole 20mg bid PO** - PPI for acid suppression and mucosal healing. Standard dose for acute gastritis. NRDL A - excellent reimbursement. Duration: 7 days (typical for acute gastritis, may extend if symptoms persist).\n\n2. **Hydrotalcite 1g tid PO** - Antacid + mucosal protectant for immediate symptom relief. Neutralizes acid, protects mucosa, provides rapid relief of epigastric pain. NRDL A. Duration: 7 days. Instructions: after meals 1-2 hours.\n\n3. **Domperidone 10mg tid PO** - Anti-emetic/prokinetic for nausea/vomiting control. Better CNS safety profile than metoclopramide (doesn't cross BBB readily). NRDL B - reasonable for symptomatic relief of vomiting. Duration: 3-5 days (shorter course as nausea/vomiting typically resolves faster than pain). Instructions: before meals.\n\nWait, I need to think about domperidone more carefully. Domperidone has some QT prolongation concerns. But for a young healthy male with no cardiac history, short-term use (3-5 days) at standard dose (10mg tid) is safe. Also, since the vomiting has been moderate (3-4 times over 2 days) and the gastritis is self-limiting, we could potentially just use PPI + antacid and not prescribe an anti-emetic, letting the PPI and antacid reduce the nausea by reducing acid irritation.\n\nActually, for acute gastritis with active vomiting, symptomatic relief with an anti-emetic is reasonable and standard practice. Let me include it but with a shorter duration (3 days).\n\n**Explicit avoidance**:\n1. Antibiotics - not indicated as there's no bacterial infection (normal WBC/neutrophils, no fever, dietary cause)\n2. NSAIDs - would worsen gastric mucosal damage; contraindicated in acute gastritis\n3. Metoclopramide (甲氧氯普胺) - more CNS side effects (extrapyramidal symptoms) than domperidone; domperidone preferred as anti-emetic in this context\n4. H2 receptor blockers (e.g., ranitidine) - less effective than PPIs for acid suppression; PPI preferred\n\n**Non-drug advice**:\n- Avoid spicy, greasy, irritating foods\n- Avoid alcohol and cold beverages\n- Eat bland, easily digestible foods\n- Small frequent meals\n- Adequate rest\n\n**Follow-up**:\n- Return in 7 days if symptoms not improving\n- Red flags: vomiting blood/coffee-ground material, black stool, worsening pain, fever\n\nNow let me construct the JSON request body. I need to be careful with the schema format.\n\nLet me think about specifications:\n- Omeprazole: typically 20mg/片 (tablet) or 20mg/胶囊 (capsule)\n- Hydrotalcite: typically 0.5g/片, so 1g = 2片\n- Domperidone: typically 10mg/片\n\nFor dose_unit, the schema allows: g, mg, μg, ml, 片, 粒, 袋, 支, 滴, U, IU\n\nI should use appropriate units:\n- Omeprazole: dose 20, dose_unit \"mg\", specification \"20mg/片\"\n- Hydrotalcite: dose 1, dose_unit \"g\", specification \"0.5g/片\" (or 2片 per dose)\n  Actually, let me think... 铝碳酸镁 is typically 0.5g/片, dosing is usually 1-2片 tid. So I could prescribe as dose 1g, dose_unit g, or dose 2, dose_unit 片. I'll use 1g since the specification says 0.5g/片 and dose is 1g.\n- Domperidone: dose 10, dose_unit \"mg\", specification \"10mg/片\"\n\nTotal quantities:\n- Omeprazole 20mg bid × 7 days = 14 tablets → total_quantity \"14片\"\n- Hydrotalcite 1g tid × 7 days = 21 tablets (0.5g/片, so 2片 per dose × 3 × 7 = 42片)... wait, that's a lot.\n  Actually, 1g per dose × 3 doses/day × 7 days = 21g total. Since each tablet is 0.5g, that's 42 tablets.\n  Hmm, let me reconsider. Maybe I should dose it as 2片 tid instead of 1g tid. Or I could use the total_quantity field.\n  \n  Actually, the common dosing for 铝碳酸镁 is 1-2片 (0.5-1g) tid after meals. Let me use 1g (2片) tid.\n  total_quantity: 42片 (for 7 days)\n\n- Domperidone 10mg tid × 3 days = 9 tablets → total_quantity \"9片\"\n\nNow let me also think about whether I should reduce the treatment duration. For acute simple gastritis:\n- PPI: 7-14 days is typical\n- Antacid: 7 days, can be PRN after\n- Anti-emetic: 3 days, should be sufficient\n\nLet me construct the prescription now.\n\nActually, I also want to think about whether I should add a mucosal protectant like sucralfate (硫糖铝) instead of or alongside hydrotalcite. But hydrotalcite already serves dual purpose (antacid + mucosal protection), so it's sufficient.\n\nLet me finalize and submit.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8ed0cd2f-d7f8-40a0-bc78-6402fc956ab1","session_id":"104c1d51-8fc0-4742-b20f-addc0682ed66"}
